\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Kappas with incomplete data:
 Inference and estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss,
 Rutger van Oest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Weighted agreement coefficients are widely used but neither inference or estimation of these coefficient for the widely encountered case of incomplete data have been properly handled.
 In this paper we illustrate and prove that common methods of handling missing data yield inconsistent estimators and incorrect standard errors.
 Then we introduce efficient estimation and inference for the weighted kappa coefficients of Fleiss,
 Conger (i.e.,
 multirater Cohen) and Brennan–Prediger for discrete data when data is missing at random.
 The estimation is based on maximum likelihood and directly generalizes the estimates and inferential methods found in the literature.
 We also present estimators for Fleiss' kappa and Brennan–Prediger for count data,
 where the estimators are consistent and efficient provided that either (a) the raters are exchangeable and data is missing at random,
 or (b) the missingness mechanism itself is exchangeable.
 Both conditions are much stronger than those required for raw data.
 We also present and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{R}$
\end_inset

 package for using these techniques and an associated 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\mathtt{C++}}}$
\end_inset

 header file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A chance-corrected agreement coefficient is any coefficient on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}=1-\frac{d}{d_{x}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a measure of disagreement and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{x}$
\end_inset

 a measure of chance disagreement.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 be a symmetric loss function satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The most common are nominal 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=1[x\neq y]$
\end_inset

,
 absolute value (or linear) 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=|x-y|$
\end_inset

,
 and quadratic 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=(x-y)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a random vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 components.
 Define disagreement as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star})].\label{eq:population disagreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We cover three variants of chance disagreement,
 the Fleiss-type,
 Cohen-type,
 and Brennan–Prediger-type.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
d_{F} & = & R^{-2}\sum_{j,k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:fleiss disagreement}\\
d_{C} & = & \binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:cohendisagreement}\\
d_{BP} & =\label{eq:bp disagreement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Interpretations of these can be found elsewhere,
 e.g.,
 [[]],
 [[]],
 [[]].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For complete data the kappa coefficients are estimated using the natural sample counterparts.
 Their standard errors may be found using either multinomial theory [cite] or 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics [Moss].
 
\end_layout

