\begin_layout Subsection
Missingness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will make the standard assumption that data is missing at random (MAR),
 the most general missingness mechanism that does not require us to model the missingness directly .
 There are many explainers for what his means in the literature,
 but mathematically speaking it reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\theta}(x\mid z)=1[x\preceq z]c(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 observed in the sample (cite [Rubin 1976,
 one more]),
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\preceq z$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a valid completion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 It's well known from the EM literature [Schafer] that the maximum likelihood estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}$
\end_inset

 can be computed by the following sequence of iterates,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{z}^{t+1}=\frac{\theta_{z}^{t}}{\sum_{x_{i}\preceq z}\theta_{z}^{t}}.\label{eq:em-step-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Details for we compute this in practice may be found in the appendix.
 By standard theory 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is consistent for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 It's asymptotically normal and efficient when the true parameter vector satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{z}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Then the asymptotic covariance matrix is the inverse Fisher information 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\theta}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Using Louis' method [cite] we may calculate the observed information
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{\theta}=-E_{\theta}[\nabla^{2}\log p_{\theta}(Z)\mid x]+\Var_{\theta}[\nabla\log p_{\theta}(Z)\mid x].\label{eq:Louis method}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $J(\theta)_{ij}=\frac{\theta}{}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

s
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's write down the three kappas in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{y^{\star}}=\frac{1}{2}\binom{R}{2}^{-1}y^{\star T}Ly^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the expected disagreement equals 
\begin_inset Formula $d(\phi)=\phi^{T}d.$
\end_inset

 The expected chance disagreement for the Brennan–Prediger coefficient is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{BP}(\phi)=c^{-2}1^{T}L1.$
\end_inset

 The Fleiss chance disagreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{F}(\phi)=p_{\phi}^{T}Lp_{\phi}.$
\end_inset

 We may write 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\phi}=M\phi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{k,y^{\star}}=r^{-1}y_{k}^{\star}$
\end_inset

,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{F}(\phi)=\phi^{T}Q_{F}\phi$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{F}=M^{T}LM$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may write these in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\Phi\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For instance,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d(\theta)=(\Phi\theta)^{T}d=\theta^{T}(\Phi^{T}d)$
\end_inset

.
 Finally,
 Cohen chance disagreement is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{C}(\theta)=\theta^{T}Q_{C}\theta$
\end_inset

,
 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{C}=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}W_{j}^{T}LW_{k},\quad(W_{j})_{k,x^{\star}}=1[x_{j}^{\star}=k].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The kappa coefficients are now written so that we may easily apply the following to apply,
 with appropriate 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta,a,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\left(1-\frac{\eta^{T}a}{\eta^{T}B\eta}\right)=-\frac{(\eta^{T}B\eta)a-(\eta^{T}a)(2B\eta)}{(\eta^{T}B\eta)^{2}},\label{eq:kappa-gradient}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

to find the gradient of Fleiss' kappa and Conger's kappa.
 The Brennan–Prediger coefficient is even easier,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla(1-\eta^{T}a)=-a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Count data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the number of raters and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be a vector of ratings with 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}\in\{1,\ldots,C\}$
\end_inset

 for component 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is finite exchangeable,
 i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(y_{1},y_{2},\ldots,y_{R})=p(y_{\sigma(1)},y_{\sigma(2)},\ldots,y_{\sigma(R)}),\quad\text{for all permutations }\sigma.
\]

\end_inset

Now define the count vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\#[y]$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\#[y]_{j}=\sum_{i=1}^{R}1[y_{i}=j]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{1,\ldots,C\}$
\end_inset

.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\#[Y]$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(Y=y)=p(Z=\#[y]).
\]

\end_inset

Since a count vector can be split into a vector on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{1},y_{2},\ldots,y_{R})$
\end_inset

,
 these representations are interchangeable.
 We will stick to the count vector representation 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 as its most illuminating.
 The count vector 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is multinomially distributed over the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}=\{Z\in R^{C}\mid\sum_{i=1}^{n}Z_{i}=R\}$
\end_inset

 which has cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{R+C-1}{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Its parameter vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{R+C-1}{R}$
\end_inset

 entries 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{z}$
\end_inset

,
 one for each 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

,
 that sum to one.
 Our job is to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{z}$
\end_inset

 from potentially incomplete data,
 and we will do this while placing no additional restrictions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

;
 this is sometimes called the 
\emph on
saturated
\emph default
 multinomial model (Schafer,
 1997).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 be the observed count vector data and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\#[y]$
\end_inset

 be the complete data.
 We will assume ignorable missingness,
 i.e.,
 the selection probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\theta}(x\mid z)=1[x\leq z]c(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 It's well known that from the expectation-maximization literature that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{z}^{t+1}=\frac{\theta_{z}^{t}}{\sum_{x_{i}\leq z}\theta_{z}^{t}}\label{eq:em-step}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

